{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015QWydTCQ7ATuXe2djZXtxM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Wire Output Mapping\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-03-09\n     4→**Status:** Proposed\n     5→\n     6→## Problem\n     7→\n     8→Host workflow steps produce output that downstream steps need as structured\n     9→input. Today the only mechanism is `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT`, a file path to the\n    10→previous step's raw output. Steps that need specific fields must parse the\n    11→output themselves, and there's no way to express \"extract field X from step A's\n    12→JSON output and inject it as env var Y into step B\" in the DSL.\n    13→\n    14→This came up immediately: `ready-tasks` outputs JSON from `bd ready --json`,\n    15→and `prepare-prompt` needs `CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE` and `CLOCHE_TASK_BODY` as env\n    16→vars. Without DSL-level mapping, every step needs bespoke shell glue.\n    17→\n    18→## Design\n    19→\n    20→### Syntax\n    21→\n    22→Output mappings live on wires, not on step declarations. A wire describes data\n    23→flow between two steps, so the mapping belongs there:\n    24→\n    25→```\n    26→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n    27→```\n    28→\n    29→The general form:\n    30→\n    31→```\n    32→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→Where:\n    36→- `KEY` is the environment variable name injected into the target step\n    37→- `EXPR` is an output path expression (see below)\n    38→\n    39→### Output Path Expressions\n    40→\n    41→All expressions start with `output`, which refers to the source step's output.\n    42→\n    43→| Expression | Meaning |\n    44→|---|---|\n    45→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n    46→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n    47→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n    48→| `output.key[N]` | Chained: field then index |\n    49→| `output[N].key` | Chained: index then field |\n    50→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01AzU8HeMxKGnzFPbbezeUQh","session_id":"b83aa53c-b539-403e-957d-d27f065bd09c","uuid":"624be4a3-c13f-4d95-96dd-866548a02bcb"}
